
readAll() (All at Once Reading)
How it works: readAll() reads the entire CSV file into memory as a List<String[]>.
Each String[] in the list represents a row (record) from the CSV file.

When it's best:
Small Files: For small to medium-sized CSV files where the entire content can easily fit into memory,
readAll() is convenient and straightforward.


Disadvantages:
Memory Intensive: This is the biggest drawback. For large files, readAll() can quickly lead
to OutOfMemoryError because it attempts to load the entire file into your application's heap space.
Performance: Can be slower for very large files as it needs to allocate and fill a large data
structure in memory before you can even start processing.

